WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:04.960
Hi everyone, my name is James Goldie. I'm the Data and Digital Storytelling Lead at 360info.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.920
Today I'm here to talk about my journey, and hopefully your journey as well,

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:13.520
from data science to animated web graphics with JavaScript.

00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:18.320
I'm sorry I can't be there in person today at PositConf, it sounds like it's really awesome.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:23.280
I am on the Discord, however, if you have any questions or ideas you want to throw at me,

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:24.160
please feel free.

00:00:24.719 --> 00:00:29.280
So I am a data journalist at 360info in Melbourne, Australia,

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:32.080
where an open newswire supported by Monash University.

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:37.200
We deliver verified and reliable information to as many publishing, broadcasting,

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:39.520
and civic society outlets as possible.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:45.759
So I lead our data efforts, I publish open graphics and data sets under Creative Commons.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:49.840
I also used to be a climate and health researcher, and I'm going to talk a bit more about

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:51.759
that transition as part of my talk.

00:00:51.919 --> 00:00:55.759
If you're following along today, the slides are available on my website

00:00:55.759 --> 00:00:57.360
down on the bottom left there.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:02.160
The code is also available, although without these lovely backgrounds.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:04.720
And of course, I'm in the Discord.

00:01:05.839 --> 00:01:09.599
So I said my career started off in research and data science,

00:01:09.599 --> 00:01:13.680
and I really moved across to communication and data journalism over that time.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:18.800
Through all that, I really looked for tools to help kind of bridge my existing technical skills.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:23.440
Quarto is a fantastic bridge, and today I really want to take you on this journey,

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:29.199
going from R or Python or Julia through to JavaScript.

00:01:30.959 --> 00:01:32.720
And I think it is a bit of a journey.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:35.839
You know, it's not something where we start in one, one day,

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:38.239
and the next day we're using JavaScript at full time.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:43.599
And that's partly because there are all these little points along the way that feel scary.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:45.040
And they don't have to be JavaScript.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:46.800
You know, one thing I really struggled with,

00:01:46.879 --> 00:01:49.760
you know, one thing I really struggled with early on was

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:53.360
just adding a style sheet to a Quarto or R Markdown document.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.519
I think a lot of us want to add our own fonts and colors to things.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:00.160
But as soon as you hear CSS, and you're like,

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:02.000
oh, I've got to learn a whole new language.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:03.040
No, no thanks.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:04.800
It feels scary.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:07.360
And that happens in JavaScript as well.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:09.520
You know, plenty of us have written a Shiny app.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:12.639
And then we hear that, you know, in order to get something done,

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:14.320
we need to add this little bit of JavaScript.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:16.479
And it feels like popping the hood on a car, you know?

00:02:17.279 --> 00:02:19.119
If you haven't learned anything about how it works,

00:02:19.119 --> 00:02:23.759
it feels like you're just kind of going down this whole layer of abstraction.

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:25.839
And that's scary.

00:02:26.559 --> 00:02:28.080
And the same thing happens in JavaScript.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:33.839
You know, D3.js is a very popular framework for making web graphics.

00:02:34.479 --> 00:02:35.919
But it's really intimidating.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.440
Same thing with the sorts of build tools that JavaScript frameworks use.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:45.919
They're often very confusing and difficult to learn if you're not a part of that world.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:51.839
But Quarto has everything we need to get started with web graphics and to start learning.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:56.160
Every journey starts with a single step.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:00.160
And our first step is going to be using observable JavaScript.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.080
Now, OJS is one of Quarto's superpowers, in my opinion.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:06.000
I think it's fantastic.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:12.639
And we're going to use OJS and a framework that comes with Quarto called observable plot

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.479
to replace the sort of graphic we might make with ggplot in R.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:20.639
And the nice thing about OJS is that you can use it right now.

00:03:21.199 --> 00:03:24.479
If you have Quarto installed, you don't need to download anything else.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:25.679
You don't need to add anything else.

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:27.520
You don't need to configure anything else.

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:29.119
If you have Quarto, you're ready to go.

00:03:29.119 --> 00:03:32.639
You can add observable JavaScript to your documents right now.

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:34.559
So here's what we're going to do.

00:03:34.559 --> 00:03:36.320
We're going to take a very basic sort of bar chart.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:42.399
And in R, we might use a chunk of R code in our Quarto document that looks like the one on the left.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:47.119
Starts with our back ticks and then our R in curly braces.

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:49.759
And we're going to do OJS instead.

00:03:49.759 --> 00:03:52.800
So instead of R in those curly braces, we're going to have OJS.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:55.440
So let's step into it.

00:03:56.559 --> 00:03:59.679
So let's say we have a very basic data set.

00:03:59.679 --> 00:04:02.800
It's a list of Australian cities and their populations in millions.

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:07.839
This is the sort of thing we might do in R.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:14.960
We're loading ggplot2, and then we are adding a mapping function, our AES, that says,

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:20.559
here are the columns in my data, city and pop, and I want to map them to the x and y axes.

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:24.799
And then we're adding layers, like our geom cold, so that we've got our bar plot.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:27.519
The rest of it is styling.

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:28.799
Yeah, I've just stripped it back a bit.

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:32.079
But I think this is very typical of like a sort of plot that someone might make with

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:34.640
some light customization and then a title at the end.

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:37.440
Now, let's see how we do this in observable plot.

00:04:38.799 --> 00:04:41.760
So we've switched from an R chunk to an OJS chunk.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:44.880
We've got a title that is actually just, it's not even part of the plot.

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.079
It's just on top because it's HTML and we can put text wherever we want.

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:49.679
Let's get into it.

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:52.079
From line six, we've got our plot function.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:56.480
Now, if you're looking at this, you're like, JavaScript looks very different.

00:04:57.359 --> 00:05:00.000
And syntactically, yeah, sure, it's a bit different.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.279
But I think if you look closely, you can see some similarities here.

00:05:03.279 --> 00:05:06.640
So we have the marks option in observable plot.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:09.279
And this is just like adding our geoms in ggplot.

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:10.880
We're adding physical layers.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:15.600
And you can see here, we've got a bar Y layer or mark, I should say.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:18.959
And inside it, as well as saying, here's the data I want to use with it.

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:20.239
We're defining our mappings.

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:22.480
This would be our AES call in ggplot.

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:27.839
And here we're saying the city column is our X axis and the pop column is our Y axis.

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:30.640
And then the rest of it, we're just doing a bit of styling to make it look pretty similar.

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:35.440
Already, we have something that is very equivalent to something we could do in R.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:40.880
And we've barely started modifying one of our existing auto documents.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:45.200
Now, how would we get that data into OJS?

00:05:45.839 --> 00:05:49.200
If you're already working in R or Python, it's very simple.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:53.519
As part of your R chunk, you would write OJS define with an underscore.

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:57.440
And then you just give it a data frame or some other piece of data you want to send across.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:58.480
And it appears.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:05:58.959
That's it.

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:04.320
You can also write out a CSV file or some other spreadsheet or other file.

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:08.160
And then you can load it back in in OJS using the file attachment function.

00:06:08.799 --> 00:06:09.920
But either way is fine.

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:15.040
So we've got our awesome plot.

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:16.399
But why would we want to do this?

00:06:17.359 --> 00:06:19.200
I mean, it is just our first step.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.079
But we can do more just static plots with OJS and the observable plot.

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:26.799
For example, observable plot has built-in tooltips.

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:34.160
So we can see here, I've added an extra layer here on top of my existing plot from before.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:35.679
So I have my plot.barY.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:40.320
And on top of that, I have plot.tip with all the same options.

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:43.040
And now we're getting tooltips for free.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:45.440
And in fact, in a lot of plots, it's simpler than this.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:49.040
We can take our plot.barY and we just add tip true to it.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:50.079
And we've got tooltips.

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:53.200
And we can customize those tooltips as well, of course.

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:57.839
But as well as that, we can actually add some accessibility options here.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:02.239
If we were just making a PNG file with ggplot,

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:05.279
we could add a description to the image as a whole.

00:07:05.279 --> 00:07:07.839
But we couldn't describe any of the individual parts of it.

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.519
With observable plot, we can actually add ARIA attributes,

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:15.359
which inject meaning into our plot, to the individual bars.

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:19.040
So we can make sure that if somebody is looking at this plot with a screen reader,

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:20.959
they can see, yes, it's a bar plot.

00:07:20.959 --> 00:07:24.079
But if they zero in on any of the individual bars,

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:28.320
they can see that Brisbane has a population of 2.28 million people.

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:30.160
Or this is a bit old now.

00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:36.000
So that lets us pack some extra meaning and accessibility into our plots.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:43.760
So we've talked about some basic examples here, just getting a flavor for OJS.

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:47.119
Now I want to take us into some more adventurous stuff.

00:07:47.119 --> 00:07:50.239
We're going to try out a few things, see a bit of what OJS can do.

00:07:53.119 --> 00:07:54.959
So here we have another observable plot.

00:07:55.679 --> 00:07:56.399
This one's a map.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:07:58.640
We've got some cities labeled around the world.

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:02.320
It's very similar to the previous observable plot graphic we did,

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.799
in the sense that you can see, again, we have our list of marks, our list of layers.

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:07.760
This time we have three.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:11.760
We have a plot.geo, which is our coastline in dark gray.

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:15.679
Then we have a layer of dots.

00:08:15.679 --> 00:08:17.600
That would be a geom point in ggplot.

00:08:18.399 --> 00:08:21.359
And then we also have a text layer, which is for our labels.

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:25.839
And you can see for each one, we've mapped an X channel and a Y channel.

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:31.359
So our longitude is our X, and our latitude is our Y, just like we do with AES in ggplot2.

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:37.119
Now this is a fine start, but I think we could make this graphic a bit more interesting.

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:41.440
So for starters, we could make it a globe.

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:44.559
And in an observable plot, that's not too hard to do at all.

00:08:44.559 --> 00:08:45.919
We can add a projection here.

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:48.719
We've added an orthographic one to make it into a globe.

00:08:49.679 --> 00:08:53.679
And it's centered on 50 longitude, which is going to be important in a second.

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:58.719
And then we've added a couple of extra layers on there for our grid lines and our sphere around it.

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:01.679
So it's not just land in space.

00:09:01.679 --> 00:09:03.119
We can see the outline of the globe.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:08.559
But we've lost half our cities because half of them are on the other side of the world.

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:10.719
It would be really nice if we could move this around.

00:09:12.719 --> 00:09:17.679
So the really nice thing about observable JavaScript is that it's reactive.

00:09:17.679 --> 00:09:21.840
Now, if you've ever used Shiny, for example, you'll know what reactivity is about.

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:26.799
If your plot includes something that is changing, your plot changes too.

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:28.559
And you don't need to tell it how to do that.

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:35.919
You don't need to say, you know, when now does this or when one thing does this, do all this logic.

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:39.440
You just refer to a thing that's changing and it changes as well.

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:43.440
So built into Quarto and OJS, we have the now object.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:45.359
And that's just a ticking clock.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:47.840
It's just number of milliseconds ticking upwards forever.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:52.159
But we can turn this into an angle with a bit of maths.

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:55.359
So we do a bit of dividing, a bit of modulus, some subtraction.

00:09:55.359 --> 00:09:59.760
And now we've got a number between negative 180 and 180.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:02.000
And you can see we don't need to do anything special here.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.200
We just refer to now and angle is changing on its own.

00:10:06.159 --> 00:10:08.159
So that's automatically updating.

00:10:08.159 --> 00:10:12.640
And now we're going to take it a step further and we're going to include angle in our plot.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:17.119
So where we had rotate 50 degrees longitude, now we have angle.

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:20.000
And so every time now changes, angle changes.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.520
And every time angle changes, our plot gets redrawn just a little bit each time.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.239
And when you do that finely enough, you get this animation,

00:10:28.239 --> 00:10:30.559
this rotation effect as it moves around.

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:35.119
As angle slowly increases, our globe rotates just a little bit more.

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:37.679
And we get this really neat rotation effect.

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:41.200
And we haven't had to do any of this logic to tie these things together.

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:42.400
We just refer to them.

00:10:44.479 --> 00:10:46.320
We can do a lot with this technique.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:50.239
And it doesn't just need to be animation in the sense of things changing over time.

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:53.760
My colleague Andrew Bray just presented CloseRead yesterday.

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:57.520
That's a Quoto extension we've been working on for scrollytelling in Quoto.

00:10:58.719 --> 00:11:02.880
With CloseRead, you can use cr-progress instead of now.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:04.559
And then you're animating on scroll.

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:08.799
So as you move this page down, that globe is twisting.

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:15.520
But sometimes we might not want to animate something necessarily.

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:20.640
We might just want to conditionally update things or change them as our circumstances change.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:24.880
Now, if you're using R or Python, you've probably seen an if-else expression.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.599
We say we give it a condition.

00:11:27.599 --> 00:11:30.000
And we say if the condition is true, give us this thing.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And if the condition is false, give us that thing.

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:34.400
And in OJS, we have that as well.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.159
The condition comes first.

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:40.159
We've got a question mark, true thing, colon, false thing.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:43.280
But the difference is in OJS, it's reactive.

00:11:43.919 --> 00:11:46.559
So it doesn't just get evaluated once when the document opens.

00:11:47.119 --> 00:11:49.200
It's evaluating continuously.

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:53.840
When the person opens the web page, whenever the condition changes, the thing changes as well.

00:11:54.559 --> 00:11:56.080
And we can do a lot with this.

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:58.479
So for example, we have a simple timer here at the top.

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:01.039
We don't need to worry about the code box.

00:12:01.039 --> 00:12:04.719
We can just see that it's ticking between 0 and 1 every couple of seconds.

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:09.280
And if we refer to this, we can now start to make some conditional content.

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:13.359
So on the bottom left, we have some just text, markdown text.

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:16.719
And you can see that's changing as the traffic light timer does.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:18.479
In the middle, we have graphics.

00:12:18.479 --> 00:12:19.840
So we've got markdown graphics.

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:22.000
We'd normally put these in a quarter document.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.440
And we can tick between two to make like a slideshow or that kind of thing.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:30.159
On the right, we have a really more complicated example where we're actually doing a drawing

00:12:30.159 --> 00:12:32.159
of some traffic lights using basic shapes.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:37.520
And you can actually see here that we had our condition embedded in here twice.

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:42.719
So our traffic light is ticking between, for the first one, black and orange.

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:45.359
And for the other one, green and black.

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:48.880
So we can do a whole bunch of different things here.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:51.599
We don't even have to use the same kind of content.

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:52.559
We can mix things.

00:12:52.559 --> 00:12:55.599
So for example, we have our city population data set here.

00:12:56.479 --> 00:12:58.320
And we've added it as a table.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:00.960
A table you'd normally think of as being an output.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:03.840
But in this case, it's also an input because we can select rows.

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:09.359
Observable, Quoto, and OJS also come with a library called Observable Inputs.

00:13:09.359 --> 00:13:12.479
And this gives us a whole bunch of user interface elements that you've seen before,

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:17.840
like checkboxes, radio boxes, drop-down menus, and in this case, a table.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:24.080
And what we're saying is that this first line up here, if we have less than three cities selected,

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:27.919
or I should say zero, one, or two cities selected,

00:13:27.919 --> 00:13:30.880
we're going to do our city plot with our bar plot.

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:32.479
And if not, we're going to show an error message.

00:13:33.039 --> 00:13:35.039
So you can see here, we've got an error message at the moment.

00:13:35.039 --> 00:13:39.599
But if I select these, as soon as we hit three, it pops up.

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:42.320
And you can see it updating still as the data changes.

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:46.400
So this selected cities is a filtered view of our data set.

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.400
We've sent in our original data set.

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:51.760
And then selected cities is the filtered version based on our selection.

00:13:55.760 --> 00:13:57.760
We can even make responsive graphics with this.

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:00.159
As well as now, we also have the width object.

00:14:00.719 --> 00:14:04.880
And you can see that if the width is over 700, we get a horizontal bar plot.

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:08.320
And if not, we'll get a vertical one, which is something I've prepared separately.

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:11.919
And as you can see, as I make the window narrower,

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:16.719
as it goes below 700, we pop to this vertical one.

00:14:17.919 --> 00:14:20.159
So now we've got something that we could use on a mobile

00:14:20.159 --> 00:14:23.039
to make this a bit more readable on a narrow layout.

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:29.119
And most of the time, this is kind of enough.

00:14:29.119 --> 00:14:32.880
Honestly, most of the graphics I build with 360 Info,

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:35.599
we're either using an external charting tool,

00:14:35.599 --> 00:14:36.960
or if I'm building something bespoke,

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:41.679
I'm using observable plot and observable inputs and OJS.

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:44.719
And this works really well because you can very effectively

00:14:44.719 --> 00:14:47.599
and quickly iterate to find the form of your graphic

00:14:47.599 --> 00:14:49.039
that's working for your audience.

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:52.559
But there are a few times when it doesn't work so well.

00:14:52.559 --> 00:14:55.280
And for me, that's often when I want to transition from A to B.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:00.479
You know, we can kind of do simulated transitions,

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:01.520
like the globe example,

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:03.760
where we had something that's ticking up over time,

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:05.919
but it's all got to be manually calculated.

00:15:05.919 --> 00:15:09.280
In OJS, when you replace one thing with another with reactivity,

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:12.719
the first thing gets destroyed immediately.

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.719
What I need is something that can see the start and the finish

00:15:16.719 --> 00:15:18.559
and smoothly transition between the two.

00:15:19.679 --> 00:15:24.080
So OJS's reactivity is lovely, but I want to bypass it sometimes.

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:25.679
And I want more control over what I draw.

00:15:26.239 --> 00:15:29.119
But I do like the declarative way I get to build graphics

00:15:29.119 --> 00:15:31.280
into gplot2 and observable plot.

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:33.760
And so the last part of our talk

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:36.479
is talking about a tool I've developed,

00:15:36.479 --> 00:15:40.640
a Quoto extension that lets me use a mature web framework

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:42.320
called Svelte in Quoto.

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:43.280
It's called Sverto.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:46.400
The funny thing about reactivity

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:48.640
is it's actually really popular these days.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:49.840
It's just about everywhere.

00:15:51.039 --> 00:15:52.000
You've seen it in Shiny,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.919
but it's also in mobile app development,

00:15:53.919 --> 00:15:57.840
most Apple and Google's main frameworks

00:15:57.840 --> 00:15:59.119
are reactive these days.

00:15:59.119 --> 00:16:01.679
And in web development, we have React, Svelte,

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:02.960
and countless others.

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:04.400
And the thing they all have in common

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:06.239
is that you make a component,

00:16:06.239 --> 00:16:08.880
you give it data or options that might change,

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:10.239
and you tell it what you want to show.

00:16:10.239 --> 00:16:13.119
And then it takes care of doing the updates

00:16:13.119 --> 00:16:14.000
when things change.

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:18.080
If this sounds really familiar,

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:21.119
I think reactivity is very philosophically similar

00:16:21.119 --> 00:16:22.400
to declarative graphics

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:24.640
because they're both about deciding

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:26.640
that we don't want to get bogged down in the details

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:29.200
of how we want to make changes to things

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:30.559
and updates to things.

00:16:30.559 --> 00:16:33.039
We just tell it what we want to focus on

00:16:33.039 --> 00:16:34.479
and it takes care of the rest.

00:16:37.359 --> 00:16:39.200
So here's Sverto.

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:41.679
This is bringing Svelte components,

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:43.280
like charts, into Quoto.

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:44.880
And those can be Svelte components

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:46.719
that someone else has made, part of the library,

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:48.159
or they can be ones you've written yourself.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:50.960
In this case, the Svelte component

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:53.280
is not the whole page, it's just the chart.

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:55.359
This is one of the really nice things about Sverto

00:16:55.359 --> 00:16:57.679
is these dropdown menus we have here on the left

00:16:58.479 --> 00:17:00.080
are actually just OJS.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:02.159
They're just the same observable inputs

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:04.239
that I used previously in the presentation.

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:06.959
But when I change them,

00:17:06.959 --> 00:17:09.520
they are updating a dataset

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:11.359
and then that dataset is going into the chart.

00:17:11.359 --> 00:17:13.199
And when the chart gets a change,

00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:14.400
like a changed data,

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:17.439
it smoothly updates the things that it's drawing.

00:17:17.439 --> 00:17:20.079
And it does so knowing where things were before

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:21.599
and where they will be next.

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:23.280
So you get these smooth transitions.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:25.520
So that could be like the colors

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:27.280
as we change from day to night,

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:28.959
as we change from Melbourne to Brisbane,

00:17:28.959 --> 00:17:32.560
looking at historical weather,

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:35.359
you can see that we're adding and removing points

00:17:35.359 --> 00:17:37.520
as we need to, fading them in and out,

00:17:38.319 --> 00:17:39.680
and we're moving them as well.

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:41.280
And you can see when we go from hottest to coldest,

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:45.280
we've also got some axes that we're using with D3.js.

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:48.079
So yeah, we've got a bit of everything here.

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:52.160
The way Sferto works,

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:54.640
it lets you write Svelte components like charts and maps

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:56.560
and bring them into Cordo quickly and easily

00:17:56.560 --> 00:17:58.000
and then drive them with OJS.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:00.319
And once you've got it installed,

00:18:00.319 --> 00:18:01.680
it's just three easy steps.

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:03.599
So use your document front matter

00:18:03.599 --> 00:18:04.800
to bring the Svelte file in.

00:18:05.359 --> 00:18:07.439
Then you tell Sferto where you wanna place it

00:18:07.439 --> 00:18:08.719
with a little bit of OJS.

00:18:09.359 --> 00:18:11.280
And then you update with OJS

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:13.520
just by assigning to properties.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:15.520
So we've brought my chart in.

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:18.719
It has a property called chart data,

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:19.760
which is our dataset.

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:22.640
And we just tied this to something that is changing.

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:25.520
Like say we've got our full dataset

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:27.359
and we're filtering it based on some menu

00:18:27.359 --> 00:18:29.199
or something of our selected year.

00:18:29.199 --> 00:18:31.599
Every time that menu changes,

00:18:32.239 --> 00:18:34.160
our filter statement runs again.

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:36.719
And then we pipe that into our chart

00:18:36.719 --> 00:18:37.920
and it changes as well.

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:39.280
And we get this smooth update.

00:18:40.079 --> 00:18:43.439
So Sferto is available on sferto.jamesgoldy.dev.

00:18:43.439 --> 00:18:44.719
I'd love for you to give it a try.

